---
import Layout from '../components/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Board meeting toolkit">
  <article class="prose-measure mx-auto px-4 py-12">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-semibold mb-2">Board meeting toolkit</h1>
    <p class="text-stone-700">Public comment is leverage. It puts your concern on the record, in front of every board member at once. These are three short scripts (about 2 minutes each) plus a short list of what to ask for and what to bring.</p>

    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-2">Finding your meeting</h2>
    <p>NY school boards must post agendas publicly in advance under Public Officers Law §103-e. Your district's Board of Education page lists the meeting calendar and (typically) the agendas as PDFs. Public comment is a standard agenda item; sign-up procedures vary by district — sometimes a sign-in sheet, sometimes an online form.</p>

    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-2">Public comment scripts</h2>
    <p class="text-stone-600 italic">Each script is roughly 2 minutes when read at a measured pace. Replace bracketed fields. The tone is intentionally calm and procedural.</p>

    <section class="mt-6 border border-stone-200 bg-white rounded p-4">
      <h3 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold mb-2">Script 1 — Data privacy compliance</h3>
      <p class="font-mono text-sm whitespace-pre-wrap">My name is [YOUR NAME]. I am a parent of a student at [SCHOOL NAME]. I am here to ask the board about the district's compliance with Education Law §2-d.

§2-d requires every NY district to post a Parents Bill of Rights for Data Privacy, sign Data Protection Agreements with every vendor that has access to student personally identifiable information, designate a Data Protection Officer, and maintain a public inventory of those vendors. Part 121 of the regulations spells out what each of those documents must contain.

I am asking three things tonight.

First, would the board direct the administration to confirm publicly that the Parents Bill of Rights is currently posted on the district website, and to share a link in the next meeting minutes.

Second, would the board direct the administration to publish, on the district website, a single page listing every contractor and service provider with access to student PII, the date of each signed Data Protection Agreement, and the supplemental information document for each.

Third, would the board confirm in the minutes the name and title of the district's designated Data Protection Officer.

These are existing legal obligations. I am asking the board to verify they are being met and to make that verification visible to parents. Thank you.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-6 border border-stone-200 bg-white rounded p-4">
      <h3 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold mb-2">Script 2 — Developmentally appropriate practice</h3>
      <p class="font-mono text-sm whitespace-pre-wrap">My name is [YOUR NAME]. I am a parent of a [GRADE]-grader at [SCHOOL NAME]. I am here about the 1:1 device program in our youngest grades.

I am not opposed to instructional technology. I am asking the board to think carefully about the developmental fit of a take-home device for children in [GRADES K-2 / K-5]. The American Academy of Pediatrics and the World Health Organization both publish cautious guidance on screen time for young children. Sweden in 2023 partially reversed its push toward early-grades tablets and restored printed books and handwriting. The research on K-5 1:1 programs is mixed at best.

Specifically, I am asking the board to consider three things.

First, whether take-home devices are pedagogically necessary for [GRADES K-2], or whether in-school use during instruction is sufficient.

Second, whether the district has reviewed the displacement effects of device-based work — handwriting, in-person discussion, outdoor time — and whether the current balance is what the board would design from scratch.

Third, whether the district publishes, in plain language for parents, what its developmentally-appropriate-practice rationale for the 1:1 program is at each grade level.

I am asking these as questions, not as a critique. Thank you.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-6 border border-stone-200 bg-white rounded p-4">
      <h3 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold mb-2">Script 3 — Procedural §2-d compliance</h3>
      <p class="font-mono text-sm whitespace-pre-wrap">My name is [YOUR NAME]. I am a parent at [SCHOOL NAME]. I am here about the district's procedural obligations under Education Law §2-d and 8 NYCRR Part 121.

Part 121 requires every district to designate a Data Protection Officer, adopt a written data security and privacy policy, maintain a data inventory, conduct annual staff training, and report data breaches in writing both to the state and to affected parents. It also requires posting a supplemental information document for every Data Protection Agreement.

I have a few procedural requests.

First, would the board direct the administration to publish, in the minutes of the next meeting, a brief status report on each of those Part 121 obligations — designation, policy, inventory, training, and breach log — with the responsible administrator named for each.

Second, would the board ask the administration to walk the board through a compliance review of §2-d and Part 121 at a meeting in the next quarter, in public session.

Third, would the board consider including a parent representative on the technology committee.

These are routine governance steps for a regulatory regime that has been on the books for over a decade. I appreciate the board's time. Thank you.</p>
    </section>

    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-10 mb-2">What to specifically ask the board for</h2>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-1">
      <li>A documented opt-out procedure for the 1:1 device program, posted in the parent handbook.</li>
      <li>Public posting of the Parents Bill of Rights, the data inventory, every signed DPA, and the supplemental information document for each.</li>
      <li>An annual data privacy impact assessment shared with the board and posted publicly.</li>
      <li>A parent representative on the district's technology committee.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-2">What to bring</h2>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-1">
      <li>A printed copy of the relevant sections of <a href="https://www.nysenate.gov/legislation/laws/EDN/2-D">NY Education Law §2-d</a> and <a href="https://www.nysed.gov/data-privacy-security/education-law-2-d-and-part-121-regulations">8 NYCRR Part 121</a>.</li>
      <li>A printed copy of the district's Parents Bill of Rights for Data Privacy, if it exists. (If you can't find it on the district site, that's a useful data point.)</li>
      <li>The names of every board member, in case you want to address them by name.</li>
      <li>A printed copy of the script — board chairs sometimes ask if you'll leave a copy for the record.</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="disclaimer mt-8">
      Public comment puts a request on the record; it is not a guaranteed response. For specific situations, consult an education attorney.
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>
